{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_ambrosia_ver01/data/sn83045774/00271744122/1921010901/0328.xml":{"full_text":"2\nStudebaker. Stuta, Templar, Valla. Weit*\ncott and Willya-Ki.ight.\nThe care being exhibited here for the\nfirst time are the DuPont, Friend. Haneon,\nHatfleld, LaFayettc, Lincoln. Lorraine,\nNoma and Piedmont.\nThe ahow comm.ttee thie year ie composed\nof John N. Willys, Willys-Overland,\nInc., chairman; Harry M. Jewett,\nPaige-Detroit Motor Car Company, and\nH. G. Hoot, Westcott Motor Cmt Company.\nThe otticers of the National Automobile\nCiutmbei of Conumrce, whleh\nlinnieaAee Vi V..ur V/.vl- uhnU Miwl *l\\\nths one In Chicago?from January US to\nFebruary 5?are as follows: Charles\nClifton, pierce-Arrow Motor Car C mpany,\npresident; Hutfh Chalmers, Chalmers\nMotor Company, vice-president; R.\nD.'Chapln. Hudson Motor Car Company,\nvloe-pi rsldent; Windsor T. White, White\nMotor Company, vice-president; C. C\nHence, Maxwell Motor Company, Inc,\nsecretary; Alfred Reeves, general manager\nJ. S. Marvin, assistant general\nmanager.\nCARS HELPlTs.'\nBACK TO NORMAL\nOakland Head Says Automobiles\nAdd to Efficiency and\nSave Money.\ni\n\"Few Individuals outside the automotive\nIndustry realize what an Important\npart the automobile Is playing\nIn the 'back to \"normal' movement,\" says\nFred W. Warner, president of the Oakland\nMotor Car Company of Pontine,\nMich. \"The automobile show season\nseems to be a good time to call the attention\nof the public to the great benefits\ngained through the passenger car.\n\"There are, I kr.ow, those who regard\nthe passenger car as an extravagance,\nbut those nersotis must be numbered\nalong with the cartoonists, jokesmitlis\nand others most guilty of this shortsighted\nmisstatement. Their personal\nattitudes are totally eclipsed by the\nfindings of the National Automobile\nChamber of Commerce, which proved by\nexacting research last summer that 90\nper cent, of all passenger cars are used\nmore or less for business.\n\"From the Oakland executive offices\nin Pontiac, Mich., we have enjoyed the\nsuccess that came from a conviction of\nthis fact. In other words, we have sold\ntransportation. The fact that the\nfarmer adds 68 per cent, to his efficiency\nby the use of a passenger car\nalso sustains our contentions. ^.nd\nfinally, when it was announced that the\naverage car owner's efficiency is Increased\n37 per cent, by use of his automobile.\nwe regarded our claims as completely\nvindicated.\n\"How ran any man, except by pointing\nto individual cases that are simply\nexceptions* dispute those findings?\nWhy, the man who uses his car for\npleasure only Is a tare being to-day!\n\"And can any one name a single\ncommodity that Is doing more to Increase\nman power and personal efficiency?\n\"Of course, there must be a compromise.\nIf this transportation is to be the\nbasis of profit, operation of the car\nmust be economical. That: is why we\nhave continued to build an automobile\nthat gets exceptional mileages on present\nday fuel and is conserving of tires.\nWe might bui'd a heavier car, but we\nPmnr.oi DUlia more bcivb.c? we*.\nwe m'ght put out a larger engine, but\nwe carvnot build a more dependable and\neconomical engine. The Oaklands r ow\nIn service?more than 200,000 of them?\nare witnesses tor our claim of economy\nof operation.\n\"We have built care for farmers, doctors,\nsalesmen, lawyers, contractors, real\nestate men, Insurance agents and about\nevery other trade or profeselon under the\naun. Consider the total Increase In efficiency\nand profit, the saving In time,\nthat these Oakland cars have accumulated\n1\n\"Freedom from timetables, freedom\nfrom the beaten highways and complete\ndisregard for weather have been gained\nby the owners of Oakland closed cars.\nJt Is Interesting to see the manner in\nwhich the farmer has adopted the sedan\nand coupe. lie reallsi-s that for complete\nsatisfaction he must have a car that con\nbe used at any time with maximum comfort\nand convenience. Being, as a type,\nn practical fel'ow. he seeks continuous\nservice and gets It to the greatest possible\ndegree In the closed car.\nThe reports of Oakland owners who\noperate their cars under the most arduous'conditions\nonly serve to strengthen\nour statement that the passenger automobile\nIs the modern means of transportation?the\nmost economical means\nwhen It Is an Oakland.\n\"Gasolene costs have mounted. To\nmaintain this eccgjomy, good mileage is\nImperative. And Oakland owners continue\nto tell us that they get from 18 to\nIS miles a gallon.\"\nThe Oakland Motor Car Company, for\nwhich President Warner speaks, is a\nmember of the General Motors Corporation\ngroup, and Is rated as the sixth\nlargest producer In the world. For several\nyears Oakland has dwelt upon\n\"transportation\" as well as the intrinsic\nvalue of the materials contained In t>e\nmachine.\nSHOW MAY BREAK PESSIMISM.\nBy Cheering 1 i> Denier* It May\nRelieve Industrial Depression.\n\"The New York Automobile Show can\nbe the means of altering the trend of\nnot only the automotive Industry, but of\nthe entire manufacturing Industry,\" said\nWilliam N. Thompson, pres dent of the\nBtutc Motor Car Company of America,\nInc., last night at the automobile show,\nwhere five Stuta models are on display.\n\"Providing only ten people attend the\nentire show. It will be a success If during\nthis week of the show the men in\nthe Industry can be awakened from the\npessimistic torpor that seems to permeate\nthe automobile atmosphere.\n\"The pessimism Is merely a state of\nmind. I>ast week, before I came Fast.\nI met a friend who Is an automobile\ndealer. His face was long and drawn\nand his entire appearance dejected.\n\"You look as though you were on your\nway to the hank.' I said. 'That's where\nI'm going,' he answered.\n\"Then 1 quest oned him shout business\nand found that he had sold more\ncars In November than he had the previous\nyear, and he also finally admitted\nthat business In December, usually a\ndull month, was gratifying. 'Rut.' he\nsaid, 'every one else In the industry\nseems dejected, and I guesa I've become\nfilled with the stagnant atmosphere\ntoo.'\n\"So It Is with the majority. And that\nIs where this year's sutomohile show\nhas a big chance to work wonders In the\nIndustry. The New York press Is doing\nail In Its power to help the situation,\nand If this great gathering of automobile\nmen ran send the members of the\nIndustry to their homes In nil pnrts of\nthe country with a smile on their faces\nand a realisation that the cloud la not\nso black ns they have made themselves\nbelieve the automobile show will have\naccomplished a great dcsl for humanity.\n\"If the automobile men return determined\nand optimistic, they will radiate\nthis confidence to other lines of endeavor\nand thus the entire country will be\nbenefited.\"\nrOI.K HKTH ECONOMY RECORD.\nfa th? Los Angrles-Yosemlte economy run.\nthe premier motor crept of the year on the\nI cosst, the Cole Aero-Eight entry turned In\nL,' a remarkable record, <>n the run of riTCS\nI miles the Cole set a mark of 40 40 ton miles\nI per gallon of fuel. The Cole used only one\n1 quart of water and three pints of oil. In\nactual gas mileage It save a mark of 17.k\nmiles I* ties gallon of feel.\nThe Motor\nBy i.J)WAUL\nPreaidant, Jordan M\nIN the last few months a remarkub\nmobile Industry.\nMany have cried \"wolf\" and\nautomobile Industry has at last reach*\nYet 9,000,000 car owners continue\nmobiles are wearing out.\nNo one has bought a horse.\nNo one has entertained for a m'\nmeans of transportation.\nYet those with stunted vision cry\nend of Its rope.\nLa-st September, when Ford saw\nsuddenly ceased.\nThe need and desire for transpor\nslop.\nEveryone Immediately felt that fu\nnent. The history of buying repeated\nOwners of cars felt that the prli\n9.000,000 oar owners did not realise th\nmeant a reduction '.n the valuation of\nMany sensed this condition and t\ntiated the best possible trade on the!\nthat the situation would change.\nThen suddenly, awakening to the\ners In an endeavor lo make a trade will\nDealer* quickly came to the point\ni be considered on the basis car owners\nThe result was stagnation In the\nFactories stopped running, parts in\nselling.\nAnd still 9,000,000 motor cars cont\nTo-day the motor industry faces\nj seen in the past.\nA new appreciation of motor car\nThe old idea Jhat purchase price wi\nNever again will the public buy\nmind that they buy shoes, clothing am\nHereafter buying will be done towi\nj In again against a new car.\nPrice will be a factor, but beyond\nmake of car?the service the manufac\ncost of upkeep the owner must meet in\nbig factors In determining price In the\nMany owners realize that the* tii\nMany are consulting their dealers am\nparticular car will reach the point of d\nWith the industry producing only\nthe last three months of 1920?with\nwith transportation by jnotor car an ec\nor marvellous in the prediction that tl\nits upward swing?\nIs it unusual to predict a renewal\nIs it astonishing that the motorini\n1 where their formula >f buying has bee\nList price, plus upkeep cost, plus d\nCOLE OPTIMISTIC\nCONCERNING 1921\nI\nSays Industry Will Equal or\nSurpass Sales Volume\nnf Pnsf Vmp.\nBy J. J. COLE,\nPresident Cole Motor Car Company.\nConsidering the many unusual circumstances\nsurrounding the business\nprocedure of the country during the past\ntwelve months the motor car Industry,\nby and large, may be said to have experienced\na most gratifying and beneficial\nyear.\ni The levelling process which always\nfollows an era of extreme prosperity has\nvisited hardships on some, but In the\nmain the substantiality of the industry\nhas been apparent and the soundness cf\n1 its business Judgment proven concluslve<\nly by its ability to adapt Itself to the\nmany variable conditions.\nj\\ Wo have learned much in the last\ntwelve* months. We are. vastlj*1 better oft\nj for the experience. On every hand wo\nsee a conscientious effort to improve, to\ntake advantage of every possibility to\nbuild upward to the most stable and dependable\nfooting, to leave no stone unturned\nin striving to give to the motoring\nworld the very best which it is possible\nto build under normal conditions.\nConsequently the year 1921 has arrived\nto find the motor oar industry in\na most hopeful frame of mind. The\naverage business for the new year gives\nevery promise of equalling, if not sur|\npassing, the volume for 1920.\nFor ourselves, we feel most happy\nover the accomplishments of our organization\nlast year. We have grown\nto a point where wore than $5,000,000\nis involved in the transaction of our affairs,\nand at oil times we have enjoyed\na cash reserve of considerably over\n$1,000,000?a sum in excess of our total\ncapitalization. Our gross receipt# for\n1920 were in the neighborhood of\n$20,000,000, and all of our operations\nhave gone forward without the necessity\nof issuing any preferred stock or bonds.\nAs for our production, we attained\nour minimum programme for the year\nwithout In any way burdening our dealers\nor distributers with any unusual responsibilities.\nThus we find our entire\nsales fabric Intact and ready for any\neffort that may be required of It during\nthe present year.\nWher* Improvements In workmanship\nor materials have been possible we have\nshown no hesitancy to put additional expenae\nInto the manufacture of the -ar.\ni Where It Is possible to cA;ate advancei\nments of any kind price has been the\ni last consideration.\nWe are persuaded that the automoi\nbile buying public Is convinced of the\nlogic of the Idea that It is not how cheap\nj but how good a product Is that deter|\nmines whether or not It Is a wise ini\nvestment\nThis Is likewise the opinion that Is\nheld by the men of the entire Industry;\nj it Is the policy which will govern the\nconstructive efforts whidh will characterize\nthe return of the automobile Industry,\nas well ss every other business,\nto a normal status.\nThe expense of operating under the\nhigh pressure of the last two yearg,*'aa\nenormous. The difficulty of obtaining\nlabor that was adequate for the task\nImposed, as well as of obtaining materials.\nInvolved expenditures which were\nappalling.\na 110 ueinRnq igr earn, wuivn iiiwicnouu\nno markedly during the last twenty-four\nmonths, will experience only an unappreclable\ndecline. The percentage of\npresent owners of cars will not be lowered\nvery considerably. Competition\nwill be quite us keen In the material and\nlabor markets as In the retail and wholesale\nmarkets of the Industry. Manufacturers\nmust take advantage 0f every\npossibility to keep their costs down as\nlow as possible without sacrificing qualI\nIty, but If they would Improve their\nproducts whenever Improvements sre\npossible present prices cannot be lowered\nvery appreciably.\nHad the automobile industry as a\ni whole been at all negligent of Its responsibility\nto the ultimate buyer of ears\nand failed toi afford one hundred cents\nof value for every dollar Invested with\nit tho phenomenal rise of this Industry\ni would not have'been accomplished.\nALLEN CARS HAVE NEW HUES.\nSapphire, Garnet, Turquoise and\nAmethyst Introdneed nt \"dim?.\nThe Allen Motor Company has gone\nhack to mother .\"vature for Its Inspiration\nand has taken to Itself the symbol\nof promise and hope of all the ages?the\nrainbow and Its colors.\nAllen cars during 1921 will be dressed\nIn the following colors, which the company\nhan named after the precious\nstones they resemble?sapphire, a handsome\ndark blue; garnet, a rich deep\nmaroon; turquoise, a light, greenish\nblue, which Is exceedingly popular, and\namethyst, a rather unusuai shade of\nviolet.\n\n8 THE\n9\nSituation.\nH. JOltDA\nolor Car Company.\nle condition has developed In the auU\nhave been loud In their claim* that th\nid the Maturation point,\nto drive their car*. Nine million autc\nnute replacing hi* car with any otM\nthat the motor lnduatry ha* reached th\nfit to out the-price of hi* car, buyln\ntatlon by motor car, however, did nc\nrther reduction* j>n all car* were 1mm\nItself.\nlb of new car* must come down. Yt\nat a reduction In the price of new car\ntheir own car*.\n'ought their dealer* at once and negt\nr old car. Many held off In the hop\npauI ^nn.lltinn IllAV thftlr deal\nnout disadvantage to themselves,\nwhore these trade-Ins could no longe\ndesired.\nbuying of motor cars.\nnkers stopped producing, dealers stoppe\ninue to run and wear out.\na future as bright and as big as evs\nvalue has developed,\nas the last price passed out with 1920.\nmotor cars with the same attitude o\n3 food.\nard the day when the car will be tradei\nthis, the value the public places on an:\nturer and dealer puts Into the car?th\ni trtalntainlng the car?these will be th\nfuture.\nne to sell their old car Is right now\nd inquiring as to the time when thel\nimlnishing returns.\nabout 20 per cent, of normal demam\n1.000,000 cars constantly wearing out?\ntonomlc fact?Is there anything unusua\n:ie motor car industry will continue o;\nof normal buying in the spring?\nS public have at last reached the poln\n:orne?\nepreciation on a resale?\nJ. J. COLE\nEXPORT AUTO PI\nrtPJJNR ST MS.TRRT1\nVA U11U AAA mnUAJUAJ\nExhibition Ts Under the At\npices of American Motors,\nIne., of This City.\nFor the first Cine in the history\nthe automobile industry a separate\nport automobile exhibition is being hi\nat the Majestic Hotel, Seventy-seco\nstreet at Central Park West. It\ncontinue until Saturday.\nDifferent In character from any ot)\nshow. Inasmuch a3 the event Is entln\nfor the development of foreign busine\nthe show, which Is under the ausph\nof the American Motors, Incorporab\nof New York, has already aroused wi<\nspread interest in export and all!\ntrades, both .locally and throughout I\ncountry, and Is creating much favoral\ncomment In the automotive lndust\nForeign visitors, consuls and represei\natlves of purchasers of automot!\nproducts abroad have expressed a\nsire to attend.\nMany of the models on display,\nthough well known throughout I\n^.South and West, have never be\nshown in New York prior to this ex\nbitlon. There also will be shown ci\nthat are built exclusively for expi\nand a chassis for which the buyer c\nbuild his own body and give It his o\ntrade name. In addition there will\nplaced on view a itandard five pnss<\ngen touring car, disassembled and pt<\nerly crated for export. The preparatl\nof cars for shipment abroad is one tl\nrequires much skill.\nThe first export automobile show p\nsents a golden opportunity for the d\ncussion of all export problems and fi\nther visualizes the rapid growth of I\nautomotive export business since I\nsigning of the armistice.\nOne of the prime factors in the pi\n(motion of American automotive pre\n\\icts In foreign fields Is the Americ\nMotors, Incorporated, distinctively\nexport organisation of many yea\nstanding, which exclusively rilstrlbu\nautomobiles, tiros trucks and trncto\nIts activities embrace every step In t\ntransfer from the American maker\nseller to the foreign buyer of any a\nall products related to the automob\nIndustry.\nThe influx of the automobile has.\nstilted In a universal demand for gr\nroads, and became of the lack of Ot)\ntransportation facilities In foreign cot\ntries the people must turn to the nu\nmobile for carriage, To-day the p;\nsenger car Is an absolute necess\nthroughout the entire world. A stu\nof the following figures brings a real!;\ntlon of the enormous opportunity thi\nIs abroad for the American manufi\nturer of passenger ears.\nThere are approximately 7,000,000 pi\nsenger cars in the United States\nday, or about one cor to every thlrt?\npersons. Europe has about IBO.OOO\npeople and approximately 130.000 passe\nger enrs. This figures out only one\nto every 1,000 persons. Taking th<\nfigures as a basis of comparison, a\nbelieving that as conditions ahroad> I\nprove our foreign neighbors will wi\nmore and more ears, there seems evt\nlikelihood that the demand will so\ncrease that there will he a market\nan automobile to every hundred p<\nsons, <fr 15,000,0no passenger cars.\nIf this country only received a certi\nproportion of this vast market fa\nWith the superior construction of c\ncars we should easily secure most\nIt), the automobile manufacturers coi\nkeep their plants going for the n?\nfew years on the export demand aloi\nThus the whole world and not 1\nTnlted States alone Is the market I\nthe American automobile manufactur\nV\nNEW YORK HERALD,\n5 cloASH HAS HIGH\nHOPES FOR 192)\nWell Known Manufacturer\nDiscusses General Business\nOutlook for Year.\n\n\"With the abundance of material wealth\ng I In thlg country to-day the buaineea outI\nlook la bound to bo most encouraging,\"\n>t I says C. W. Nush, president of the Nash\nMotors Company and one of the country's\nforemost manufacturers,\nit \"America Is to-day the richest nation\n8 In the world. This will not be queaH\ntloncd- For some years past we have\ne acted as the main source of supply for\nother oountrles. The volume of our\nproduction In most lines,has been limited\nonly by our ability to produce and\nr not by the size of the demand.\n\"Our products have been sold at *op\nprices. In payment for these products\nthere has been a steady flow Into ihis\nCountry of the money of the world' I'ntll\nAmerica, Instead of being saddled by\n9 stupendous financial obligations, as are\ni most of the other countries, stands in\nthe envlaffle position of being the world'B\nf/asi <?stv?crftaiftBt money dowjP\namong nations.\n\"As a nation we are more than sol\nvent We have a handsome balance on\nthe right side of the ledger. And this\ny wealth Is not concentrated In the hands\n0 of a few Individuals. It le spread\n6 through every Industry and every layer\nof the nation's economic life.\n4 \"Business has Just passed through the\nr most profitable era in Its history on the\nAmerican continent. Sales totals have\npassed all previous marks and profits\nhave been corresponds rty good.\n\"This naturally brought with it a pen\nrlod of unprecedented prosperity for\nlabor, which has received more for Its\nservices?In tnany instances?for a single\nI day than it formerly received In a week.\n\"Farmers, too, have shared abundantly\nIn these general good times.\n\"The point I am making is that there\nIs wealth, a great amount of wealth,\nrt throughout the land. This, of course,\ni is fundamentally important. It Is the\nground upon which I base my conviction\nthat the readjustment through which\nwe are Just passing is to be followed\nby. a period of good business. By this\nI do not mean boom business such as\nI Immediately preceded the present dcflai\ntlon' process, but business conditions\nwhich will be a great deal more stable\nand sound.\n\"My confidence In the average Amerl|\ncan business man and his administrative\nability is great. I know that, taken collectively,\nhe Is the best business man\nin the world. I do not believe this is\nmere patriotic talk, but feel that the\nfacts bear me out.\n\"So I feel certain that he Is a big\nenough executive to go through a necessary\nperiod of deflation and emerge\nstronger and more secure than he was\nbefore.\n\"In short, my confidence In the Amer\nlean nusiness man, oaeKea as ne is Dy\nthe nation's wealth, leads me to be most\nhopeful over the business outlook for\nthe future.\n\"It Is true that we are rlsrht now uni\ndergolng a readjustment whioh was neofe.-sary\nand Inevitable and which, to my\nmind, is bound to have a good effect\nupon the entire country,\nj \"This readjustment means a squeezing\nJ j 'ft of fictitious values and a getting\nback upon a more substantial and permanent\neconomic foundation.\n\"That this readjustment is rapidly\nnearlng completion is Indicated by the\nf fact that for some lltfte time past there\nhas been reported by the banks an Increasing\nturnover of money. This is always\na good sign,\nrrj \"A process of liquidation Is taking\n\\J p,ace which s putting the money of\nthe country into healthier lines of business\nenterprise. While the banks report\nno radical reduction in the total\namount of loans they do report an increasing\nliquidation of outstanding obligations\nand a conoequent Increase of\nnew loans, which means that the nation's\nmoney is going back to work again and\nthat h\"yi- g power is on the increase.\n\"I shoiild sny offhand that every dollar\nraid in on an old debt increases the\nof buying capacity of the country to the\n,x_ extent of about $5.\n\"By way of illustration: If a man\neld owes you a dollar and pays it you have\nnd a dollar more with which to buy and\nirjii the man from whom you buy has another\ndollar with which he may purchase\nand so on, throughout the circle.\n1?r \"The present condition of business ln8\ny dlcates pretty clearly to me that there\nis bound to be an Improvement In the'\nbuying market In automobiles and kinje_'\ndred 1 ties in which I am. of course,\nle(j primarily interested, but that business\nas whole soon will be. to quote the old\nelogan, \"Carrying on as usual.\"\n\"t- AUTOMOBILE NOT YET PERFECT\nIve\nlf\" Metnllnrglcal Improvements Will\nat- Come, Frank Natl, Engineer, Says.\n'10 \"In no other industry aye the demands\nn for high grade steel so great as In the\n1 automobile Industry,\" Frank N. Nutt,\nchief engineer of the Haynes Automobile\n1 Company ,mM recently. \"In no other In\"n\ndu'stry are the Intricacies of the science\nbe i nf me,alIuW 80 studiously applied as In\nthe manufacture of automobllea\n\"The slow speed Internal combustion\nengine and the easygoing horse drawn\nt vehicle of a few decades ago could be\nconstructed of ordinary steel. The combination\nof the internal combustion enI\ngine and the carrlnge into a high speed,\njr\" self-propelled vehicle necessitated light\nweight parts of great strength and\nwearing qualities.\n\"Fortunately all branchea of aclenca\ntend to keep pace with each other, and\n\"T 